message: Today I want you to help with a specific strand of Research for the Edinburgh City Council’s Public art research Project.
You will take me on a curated experience involving three works of art; art that is transformative, contentious, and new.
Are you ready to get started?
Please take me to a public work of art that is transformative...
Ok, let me know when we get there.
\What are we looking at? Take a pic and tell me it’s name.\
Alright, I am gonna ask some deep questions now.
Who or what is this transformative for and why?
This art work was part of a project to refurbish and transform an existing staircase and important route between the Old and New Towns.

Users of the Steps are able to enjoy the transformation that has taken place. The stone Steps have been overlaid in Marble. This artwork was conceived by Martin Creed. Each marble was carefully selected. Each step is a different marble from a different geographical location. The ascent/descent of the Steps takes you on a journey to all those countries. The overall assembly is very attractive.

The Steps used to be a place of antisocial behaviour and people were afraid to use the route. The artwork encourage more footfall and consequently it is a safer better environment. The artwork encourages the owner- CEC, to take pride in the stairway and maintain it better than before. Everyone benefits.

Could you please expand on the quality, taste, and appropriateness of this work of art?
Focus on any or all points and take a pic if it helps.

Each marble is individually  beautiful and many textures and colours have been chosen. My favourites are the one photographed which looked like it has living veins through it, and the blue one on the very top step. The detailing and workmanship was to the highest quality. It feels as though the Steps were always built of marble.

Could you expand on the context about this work of art?

The idea came to EWH to reinvigorate the Steps through conservation of the historic structure and public art. The fruit market gallery joined up with them and CEC to develop a project after the police had concerns that it was only a matter of time until there was a murder there. Martin Creed was chosen. This was not the first idea that he had for the Steps but it is more successful. The opening was timed to be part of an exhibition at the gallery. The theme of the exhibition was inspired by the Steps project.
Would you like to say anything else about this work of art or any issue related?
Please take me to a public work of art that is contentious...
Ok, let me know when we get there.
\What are we looking at? Take a pic and tell me it’s name.\
What makes this work of art contentious? And for whom?

This a statue of William Playfair, architect. It is contentious because it is a new statue in a 'historic' style. It could deceive tourists into thinking about that it was made in the 18 th century. Some people would say that this is dishonest or inauthentic, that a more contemporary style should be used. It is also contentious to erect such a statue of a man at a time when there is a growing realisation that too few women from history or current times have been commemorated. Is it appropriate to fill the city with more statues of white men? Young women today want to see role models more relevant to them. It may als be contentious in that it's location required another existing statue to be relocated to face the new one. Some people feel that it was not appropriate to do thA. The statue of William Chamber is somehow diminished by the new scheme. It previously dominated the street ( as it was designed/ intended to do. I also find the materials and size ( and choice of sculptor) contentious as it was very expensive. It was commissioned by a few wealthy and influential men in this city. Is it fair that the city only gains the new public  art that this narrow group favour? art
Our research shows contention raises issues of inclusivity and exclusivity... Does this work of art have issues with inclusivity and exclusivity?
What are the issues and affected parties? Take a pic if it helps...

As I said, it is another white man ( we have a lot of similar statues already) do women feel this right/ fair? It was commissioned by influential people with the ability raise significant funds, how do less wealthy people go about influencing/ choosing public art that represents their values/ interests?

Not sure if either of these are relevant to this case other than the risk that Edinburgh is seen as 'stuck in the past '.

Tell me about it and take a pic if it helps...
The style and materials are very appropriate for the setting but possibly prohibitively costly for most projects in the economic environment we have today.

Our research shows the process for a public art project can lack transparency for interested parties. Given the place and potentiality for a work of art here, can you imagine what a transparent process would be?
Please give me insight by steps or association and order-of groups involved.

Workshops to create a strategy. Public engagement throughout process. In formation on website and on site to explain what is proposed. Add gallery of modern art to group to advise on strategy if necessary.
